    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3271919343" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3271919343" />
    <a title="Amy Layton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6307179-amy-layton"><img alt="Amy Layton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1489002128p2/6307179.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3271919343?book_show_action=true">Apr 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amy Layton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amy Layton" href="/user/show/6307179-amy-layton">Amy Layton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6307179-amy-layton?shelf=plays">plays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3271919343" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5451876498372097452">I&apos;m not quite sure what to think of this play.  I&apos;ve been sitting at my desk for quite a few minutes, head in hands, trying to think of what I might be able to say.  I liked this.  A lot.  So much, even, that when it comes to my area, I should very much like to see it.  After all, plays are meant for the stage.  <br/><br/>I&apos;m giving this a four, because I feel like I&apos;m missing something, and I&apos;m not quite sure if that&apos;s the point.  It&apos;s a memory play, and memories are often missing something, but still ha</span>
  <span id="freeText5451876498372097452" style="display:none">I'm not quite sure what to think of this play.  I've been sitting at my desk for quite a few minutes, head in hands, trying to think of what I might be able to say.  I liked this.  A lot.  So much, even, that when it comes to my area, I should very much like to see it.  After all, plays are meant for the stage.  <br /><br />I'm giving this a four, because I feel like I'm missing something, and I'm not quite sure if that's the point.  It's a memory play, and memories are often missing something, but still have that feeling of deja vu.  And the characters are all missing something as well--a grasp on reality.  It's easier to hide into what we want to make of ourselves--a southern belle, a drunk poet, a shy and fanciful girl.  But it's more difficult to actually be them.  To be such things, a belle, a poet, a fanciful girl, requires time and money and effort.  For the most part, though, it's easier to pretend to be such things and go off to a job you hate, to make excuses as to why the house is falling apart, to forgo lessons because of severe social anxiety.  <br /><br />Or perhaps what I'm missing is that it's intrinsically reflective of my own insecurities, and I simply refuse to believe it.  This almost seems to be an antithesis to Vonnegut's Mother Night, in which "we are what we pretend to be," whereas this play seems to say that pretending just simply isn't enough, and who are we really fooling, anyways?  If we can't even fool ourselves, what's the point?<br /><br />What I really adored about this play, though, was the fact that the ending was both realistic and utterly depressing.  The lights have been shut off, the gentleman caller is taken, glass toys break, and sons become just like their fathers.  <br /><br />I think I'll have to read this one again in a couple years.  Perhaps when I'm older, I'll understand more, be more well-read, have more empathy and understanding under my belt.  It's a beautiful play, and it certainly deserves attention.<br /><br />Review cross-listed <a href="http://www.littleladylibrarian.wordpress.com" rel="nofollow noopener">here</a>!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5451876498372097452" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


