    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3683154509" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3683154509" />
    <a title="Deborah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9813309-deborah"><img alt="Deborah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1561124201p2/9813309.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3683154509?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deborah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deborah" href="/user/show/9813309-deborah">Deborah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3683154509" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15860614277312373456">The Glass Menagerie propelled Tennessee Williams into success as a playwright when it was first performed in 1944. It has been made into movies. It has been analyzed by critics. To this day it is still performed. Why is it so popular? It is a family drama of tensions and alienation. To escape their demons, the family faces abandonment, sacrifices, confinement, and misunderstandings. It is a reflection of Tennessee’s family, where his troubled sister underwent a prefrontal lobotomy. <br/><br/>The son, Tom </span>
  <span id="freeText15860614277312373456" style="display:none">The Glass Menagerie propelled Tennessee Williams into success as a playwright when it was first performed in 1944. It has been made into movies. It has been analyzed by critics. To this day it is still performed. Why is it so popular? It is a family drama of tensions and alienation. To escape their demons, the family faces abandonment, sacrifices, confinement, and misunderstandings. It is a reflection of Tennessee’s family, where his troubled sister underwent a prefrontal lobotomy. <br /><br />The son, Tom Wingfield, who is miserable and craves change and adventure, introduces himself as the narrator. This memory play is not realistic but sentimental and dimly lit with a background of music and an ever changing images. The mother, Amanda, is desperate, nagging, and overly devoted. The daughter, Laura, is painfully shy and fragile. Each withdraws into their worlds by escaping the drudgery and realities of their reduced circumstances by drinking and watching movies for Tom, by obsessing and animating her glass animal collection for Laura, and by reliving the memories of her Southern past for Amanda. Jim O’Connor, the gentleman caller, is social and striving to better his life. As Laura’s prospects for work seemed dashed, the mother vigorously pursues a campaign of matrimony on her behalf. I was impressed and overwhelmed with the play from its characters, its message, its ingenuity, and its believability. It is a sad play seeking hope. The music and images adds to the drama. It is a timeless masterpiece. I highly recommend. I cannot wait to see a performance of the play.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15860614277312373456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

